00:03:00.170 --> 00:03:02.610
So again, what
we're looking at--

00:03:02.610 --> 00:03:05.230
we're putting you in
the shoes of WidgetCo.

00:03:05.230 --> 00:03:08.120
Essentially you are
a chair manufacturer

00:03:08.120 --> 00:03:13.409
selling office-type chairs,
where you manufacture them.

00:03:13.409 --> 00:03:14.700
You own your own manufacturing.

00:03:14.700 --> 00:03:16.870
You sell primarily to
customers in the US,

00:03:16.870 --> 00:03:20.690
both at the retail level
and to industrial consumers.

00:03:20.690 --> 00:03:23.120
Facilities-wise, you have
two manufacturing plants.

00:03:23.120 --> 00:03:25.040
One is located in Shanghai.

00:03:25.040 --> 00:03:27.762
The one is located
here in US in Michigan.

00:03:27.762 --> 00:03:29.220
The one in Michigan
is fully owned.

00:03:29.220 --> 00:03:31.730
The one in China as
a 50-50 joint venture

00:03:31.730 --> 00:03:34.094
with local investors.

00:03:34.094 --> 00:03:35.510
You have two
distributions centers

00:03:35.510 --> 00:03:38.020
in the US-- one in
California and one in Georgia

00:03:38.020 --> 00:03:40.670
that you use for finished goods.

00:03:40.670 --> 00:03:44.480
And you also have a partnership
with a large retailer that

00:03:44.480 --> 00:03:46.700
sets aside some dedicated
space within each

00:03:46.700 --> 00:03:54.310
of their large big box retailers
dedicated to just showcasing

00:03:54.310 --> 00:03:55.670
your products.

00:03:55.670 --> 00:03:56.850
Transportation.

00:03:56.850 --> 00:04:00.050
You use a 3PL to bring in
imported materials and finished

00:04:00.050 --> 00:04:00.550
goods.

00:04:00.550 --> 00:04:03.020
So you have the
raw materials that

00:04:03.020 --> 00:04:06.910
come in by ocean that get sent
to your factory in Michigan.

00:04:06.910 --> 00:04:08.530
You also have
finished chairs coming

00:04:08.530 --> 00:04:10.070
in from the plant in China.

00:04:10.070 --> 00:04:15.150
Those come in over a dedicated
3PL by ocean to get to the US

00:04:15.150 --> 00:04:18.019
and then by rail and by
truck once they arrive.

00:04:18.019 --> 00:04:20.421
For the retail channel,
you service that primarily

00:04:20.421 --> 00:04:21.670
with your private truck fleet.

00:04:21.670 --> 00:04:23.211
So you own a fleet
of trucks that you

00:04:23.211 --> 00:04:24.966
use to deliver to retailers.

00:04:24.966 --> 00:04:26.340
And then you make
up for the rest

00:04:26.340 --> 00:04:27.840
of the volume that
you can't handle,

00:04:27.840 --> 00:04:30.670
either by air or by lessened
truckload shipments.

00:04:30.670 --> 00:04:32.710
And finally, for the
industrial channel,

00:04:32.710 --> 00:04:37.880
most of your customers, they
actually come and pick it up.

00:04:37.880 --> 00:04:39.910
So you don't handle
that transportation.

00:04:39.910 --> 00:04:41.990
The remaining 40% are
done by deliveries.

00:04:41.990 --> 00:04:44.260
I think it was by LTL.

00:04:44.260 --> 00:04:46.520
So that's basically
what we have here,

00:04:46.520 --> 00:04:49.670
is sort of the
supply chain flow.

00:04:49.670 --> 00:04:52.450
Most of your suppliers
are located off in China.

00:04:52.450 --> 00:04:54.960
That's where your raw materials
and parts of coming to,

00:04:54.960 --> 00:04:59.300
shipping it out to your plants
in Michigan and Shanghai.

00:04:59.300 --> 00:05:02.960
Again, this in channel,
all this goes on in the US.

00:05:02.960 --> 00:05:05.520
And just if we look at
it in terms of this flow,

00:05:05.520 --> 00:05:08.600
this is sort of where our
transportation has come in.

00:05:08.600 --> 00:05:12.260
So pretty straightforward and
simplified example of a supply

00:05:12.260 --> 00:05:13.950
chain.

00:05:13.950 --> 00:05:16.170
And the goal is to go
through and figure out

00:05:16.170 --> 00:05:18.730
what your carbon footprint is
based on a couple of things,

00:05:18.730 --> 00:05:19.230
right?

00:05:19.230 --> 00:05:21.520
You're getting pressure
from investors.

00:05:21.520 --> 00:05:23.920
You're getting it maybe
from some of your customers

00:05:23.920 --> 00:05:24.820
asking about it.

00:05:24.820 --> 00:05:26.920
So now it's starting
to get some attention

00:05:26.920 --> 00:05:28.980
within the organization,
from the CEO.

00:05:28.980 --> 00:05:30.750
And basically you're
the one put in charge

00:05:30.750 --> 00:05:32.740
of figuring out what that is.

00:05:32.740 --> 00:05:35.300
The pressure's sort
of ratcheting up.

00:05:35.300 --> 00:05:39.540
So FerretCo is basically
your main direct competitor.

00:05:39.540 --> 00:05:43.255
They operated a little
bit lower price point.

00:05:43.255 --> 00:05:44.880
But they're starting
to try to increase

00:05:44.880 --> 00:05:47.560
their profile by doing some of
the sustainability initiatives.

00:05:47.560 --> 00:05:49.680
So part of that is they want
to move into the retail space,

00:05:49.680 --> 00:05:51.200
whereas previously
they've mainly

00:05:51.200 --> 00:05:52.410
served industrial companies.

00:05:52.410 --> 00:05:55.750
So as part of that, they've
released their carbon footprint

00:05:55.750 --> 00:05:58.120
publicly disclosed in the
carbon Disclosure Project.

00:05:58.120 --> 00:06:01.190
And that came out at
55,000 tons of CO2.

00:06:01.190 --> 00:06:03.350
Based on their sales
and their product,

00:06:03.350 --> 00:06:05.550
that was 1.1
kilograms per product.

00:06:05.550 --> 00:06:07.380
So that's aggregate emissions.

00:06:07.380 --> 00:06:10.930
And this is sort of a
per-product or per-unit level.

00:06:10.930 --> 00:06:12.680
They've also announced
a plan that they're

00:06:12.680 --> 00:06:14.220
going to become carbon neutral.

00:06:14.220 --> 00:06:16.670
And also they're exploring
putting a carbon label

00:06:16.670 --> 00:06:18.709
on their retail products.

00:06:18.709 --> 00:06:20.250
A new entry into
the market-- they're

00:06:20.250 --> 00:06:23.330
trying to appeal directly
to the end consumers

00:06:23.330 --> 00:06:27.410
that they'll be
trying to sell to.

00:06:27.410 --> 00:06:30.230
So with that in place, if
we look at the supply chain,

00:06:30.230 --> 00:06:32.680
we have a number of different
emission sources, right?

00:06:32.680 --> 00:06:35.050
We have all these different
transportation pieces

00:06:35.050 --> 00:06:36.970
that are linking
these different flows

00:06:36.970 --> 00:06:38.220
that we have some data for.

00:06:38.220 --> 00:06:40.726
We have emissions
coming from our plants,

00:06:40.726 --> 00:06:42.600
in terms of electricity
and direct emissions.

00:06:42.600 --> 00:06:46.020
So obviously you're
consuming electricity

00:06:46.020 --> 00:06:49.590
that generated emissions of
PowerPoint when it was created.

00:06:49.590 --> 00:06:51.340
You also might have
some direct emissions.

00:06:51.340 --> 00:06:53.090
We don't specify where
that's coming from,

00:06:53.090 --> 00:06:55.420
but you might be burning
natural gas or fuel

00:06:55.420 --> 00:06:57.430
oil in the facilities.

00:06:57.430 --> 00:06:59.890
Other types of
manufacturing processes--

00:06:59.890 --> 00:07:01.720
might release
chemicals directly,

00:07:01.720 --> 00:07:03.330
especially in chemicals.

00:07:03.330 --> 00:07:04.780
Agricultural companies, right?

00:07:04.780 --> 00:07:06.980
They produce other types
of direct admissions.

00:07:06.980 --> 00:07:11.140
But we'll just leave it as
direct emissions in this case.

00:07:11.140 --> 00:07:13.140
You also have some of
these different facilities

00:07:13.140 --> 00:07:14.500
that are consuming electricity.

00:07:14.500 --> 00:07:18.450
So if your DCs and also
what's going on at-- you

00:07:18.450 --> 00:07:23.450
have those dedicated little
show rooms in big depot.

00:07:23.450 --> 00:07:27.680
So this is essentially
the calculation

00:07:27.680 --> 00:07:28.680
set up that we gave you.

00:07:28.680 --> 00:07:31.600
I do want to go over
just two quickly.

00:07:31.600 --> 00:07:35.180
So first, facility is pretty
straightforward-- electricity

00:07:35.180 --> 00:07:36.920
consumption times
the emissions factor.

00:07:36.920 --> 00:07:39.790
This is in general how basically
every calculation goes, right?

00:07:39.790 --> 00:07:41.070
You have these
emissions factors that

00:07:41.070 --> 00:07:43.319
are published by organizations
like the Greenhouse Gas

00:07:43.319 --> 00:07:47.902
Protocol that are going to tell
you what the emissions are--

00:07:47.902 --> 00:07:48.860
four different factors.

00:07:48.860 --> 00:07:50.904
So different fuel types
and different electricity

00:07:50.904 --> 00:07:52.320
consumptions, where
they're going.

00:07:52.320 --> 00:07:53.850
How much do they emit?

00:07:53.850 --> 00:07:55.840
And then basically it's
your job to gather data

00:07:55.840 --> 00:07:58.640
about how much you consumed
or how much of that material

00:07:58.640 --> 00:08:01.932
you used, a factor in
the direct emissions.

00:08:01.932 --> 00:08:04.140
For some of these other
things, when that data is not

00:08:04.140 --> 00:08:06.800
available-- especially if this
is the case in transportation--

00:08:06.800 --> 00:08:09.008
you might have a choice of
several different methods.

00:08:09.008 --> 00:08:12.020
So in this case, we had
two different ones-- one

00:08:12.020 --> 00:08:15.180
based on ton-miles and one
based on fuel consumption.

00:08:15.180 --> 00:08:18.410
So this would generally be
the preferred choice-- fuel

00:08:18.410 --> 00:08:21.322
consumption-- mainly
because it's simple.

00:08:21.322 --> 00:08:22.780
If you know how
much fuel consumed,

00:08:22.780 --> 00:08:23.880
you know the
emissions factor, you

00:08:23.880 --> 00:08:25.650
know how much
emissions it produce.

00:08:25.650 --> 00:08:29.170
And in cases like
diesel or gasoline,

00:08:29.170 --> 00:08:31.840
the CO2 emissions are
pretty much directly tied.

00:08:31.840 --> 00:08:34.309
It's basically a one-to-one
correspondence in terms of,

00:08:34.309 --> 00:08:36.520
every gallon of fuel you
consume is going to produce

00:08:36.520 --> 00:08:37.919
a set amount of emissions.

00:08:37.919 --> 00:08:40.179
It's not going to
change too much.

00:08:40.179 --> 00:08:42.856
So you'd like to get to
that fuel consumption.

00:08:42.856 --> 00:08:44.730
But that's not always
easy to get, especially

00:08:44.730 --> 00:08:46.396
when you're hiring a
third-party carrier

00:08:46.396 --> 00:08:48.600
or, more importantly,
when you're using

00:08:48.600 --> 00:08:50.066
shared transportation assets.

00:08:50.066 --> 00:08:51.440
So on a dedicated
transportation,

00:08:51.440 --> 00:08:52.890
I hire a truckload company.

00:08:52.890 --> 00:08:55.076
They come up, they put
my goods on the truck,

00:08:55.076 --> 00:08:56.200
and they take it someplace.

00:08:56.200 --> 00:08:57.780
It's nothing but
my goods on there.

00:08:57.780 --> 00:09:00.321
So all of the emissions that
are generated when that truck is

00:09:00.321 --> 00:09:03.060
going would be dedicated to me.

00:09:03.060 --> 00:09:05.150
So I can just try to
maybe make an estimate

00:09:05.150 --> 00:09:08.319
of the fuel consumed and get
how much the emissions would be.

00:09:08.319 --> 00:09:09.860
When you're looking
at rail or ocean,

00:09:09.860 --> 00:09:11.360
where an ocean ship
might have thousands

00:09:11.360 --> 00:09:12.984
of different containers
on it and maybe

00:09:12.984 --> 00:09:15.030
only one or two of
those are your goods,

00:09:15.030 --> 00:09:16.710
you're not really
interested in how much

00:09:16.710 --> 00:09:20.480
the total ship or the total
rail car might have emitted.

00:09:20.480 --> 00:09:25.210
You want to know how much is
essentially dedicated to you.

00:09:25.210 --> 00:09:27.780
So in this case, usually
what we do is that.

00:09:27.780 --> 00:09:30.270
We would measure the
efficiency of the vehicles

00:09:30.270 --> 00:09:32.065
in terms of how much
fuel they consume

00:09:32.065 --> 00:09:35.130
or emissions they all
put per ton-mile, right?

00:09:35.130 --> 00:09:39.240
So a ton-mile is a
pretty common indicator

00:09:39.240 --> 00:09:41.510
in the transportation, right?

00:09:41.510 --> 00:09:46.660
And that's just 1
ton times 1 mile.

00:09:46.660 --> 00:09:52.280
If you move one ton of goods
one mile, that's one ton-mile.

00:09:52.280 --> 00:09:53.465
So you can think about it.

00:09:53.465 --> 00:09:56.090
If you have 20 tons on there and
you go one mile, 20 ton-miles.

00:09:56.090 --> 00:09:57.740
So if you had one
ton and you took it

00:09:57.740 --> 00:10:00.142
20 miles, also 20 ton-miles.

00:10:00.142 --> 00:10:01.600
The reason we would
do it like this

00:10:01.600 --> 00:10:05.180
is because generally those
larger vehicles-- the larger

00:10:05.180 --> 00:10:08.240
the ocean ship goes, the
more fuel it consumes, say,

00:10:08.240 --> 00:10:10.050
per kilometer that it moves.

00:10:10.050 --> 00:10:12.360
But as it's starting
to aggregate,

00:10:12.360 --> 00:10:14.369
it carries more and
more goods on it.

00:10:14.369 --> 00:10:16.410
So it's actually becoming
more efficient in terms

00:10:16.410 --> 00:10:17.960
of the actual goods
that it moves,

00:10:17.960 --> 00:10:20.060
because it can move
a lot more product

00:10:20.060 --> 00:10:24.200
that same amount of distance
on a less amount of fuel.

00:10:24.200 --> 00:10:26.930
So lower fuel consumption.

00:10:26.930 --> 00:10:28.900
The trick with this--
and this is something

00:10:28.900 --> 00:10:32.560
that tripped a few
of you up on it--

00:10:32.560 --> 00:10:34.510
is when you have
aggregated data, right?

00:10:34.510 --> 00:10:36.350
So if you look at
the data that we had,

00:10:36.350 --> 00:10:38.680
we don't have a breakdown
of every single shipment,

00:10:38.680 --> 00:10:42.006
especially when you're a company
that's maybe making thousands

00:10:42.006 --> 00:10:43.130
and thousands of shipments.

00:10:43.130 --> 00:10:45.870
You may not have a direct
record of every single shipment

00:10:45.870 --> 00:10:50.010
that you send, in terms of its
distance and its total tonnage.

00:10:50.010 --> 00:10:51.810
So what you might
get is something

00:10:51.810 --> 00:10:52.840
like what we gave you.

00:10:52.840 --> 00:10:58.660
Say you knew that you had--
let's do a quick example.

00:11:11.500 --> 00:11:13.590
Say we just add two shipments.

00:11:13.590 --> 00:11:14.730
That's all we sent.

00:11:14.730 --> 00:11:18.140
And the first one, I had 10 tons
on it and I sent it 10 miles.

00:11:18.140 --> 00:11:18.890
So pretty simple.

00:11:18.890 --> 00:11:20.314
That's 100 ton-miles.

00:11:20.314 --> 00:11:21.730
The second one,
we have five times

00:11:21.730 --> 00:11:23.550
and we send up five miles.

00:11:23.550 --> 00:11:24.820
That's 25 ton-miles.

00:11:24.820 --> 00:11:30.750
So in total, I moved 125
ton-miles' worth of goods.

00:11:30.750 --> 00:11:34.150
The trick is this, is that if
we were to aggregate this--

00:11:34.150 --> 00:11:38.285
and this is what you are
given in the exercise.

00:11:38.285 --> 00:11:41.940
You know something like,
you sent two shipments.

00:11:41.940 --> 00:11:44.530
And you moved a total 15 tons.

00:11:44.530 --> 00:11:47.810
And you moved a total
of 15 miles, right?

00:11:47.810 --> 00:11:49.500
The problem is that
if you try to take

00:11:49.500 --> 00:11:52.490
these aggregated numbers and
just multiply them together--

00:11:52.490 --> 00:11:53.605
15 times 15.

00:11:56.260 --> 00:11:57.450
It's 225, right?

00:11:57.450 --> 00:11:59.780
It's very different from
what you actually did.

00:11:59.780 --> 00:12:01.740
And this goes back to our--

00:12:07.550 --> 00:12:10.090
If we go all the way
back to, I don't know,

00:12:10.090 --> 00:12:12.340
our junior high math, right?

00:12:12.340 --> 00:12:16.615
A times B plus C times
D. That does not equal--

00:12:24.130 --> 00:12:24.940
Right.

00:12:24.940 --> 00:12:29.150
So I can't add these two and
add these two and multiply them.

00:12:29.150 --> 00:12:30.550
You just get a different number.

00:12:30.550 --> 00:12:33.280
So if you just
take the aggregate

00:12:33.280 --> 00:12:35.280
you did, especially when
we had 1,000 shipments.

00:12:35.280 --> 00:12:38.020
So you moved 26 million
miles or whatever it was,

00:12:38.020 --> 00:12:40.454
and you moved 50
million kilograms

00:12:40.454 --> 00:12:41.870
and just multiplied
them together.

00:12:41.870 --> 00:12:44.930
You got some really huge number.

00:12:44.930 --> 00:12:46.730
And it probably threw
off the calculations.

00:12:46.730 --> 00:12:48.855
You ended up having, say,
your ocean transportation

00:12:48.855 --> 00:12:51.660
or something being by far the
largest source of emissions.

00:12:51.660 --> 00:12:55.200
So that's just one
thing to look out for.

00:12:55.200 --> 00:12:57.520
When we've done this--
we've given this in the past

00:12:57.520 --> 00:13:00.000
with the executive
ed participants.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:02.640
And 99% of them always
do the same thing.

00:13:02.640 --> 00:13:06.130
So I knew that would
possibly trip you up.

00:13:06.130 --> 00:13:08.580
But I think in the
examples that we gave,

00:13:08.580 --> 00:13:10.680
we broke it out is that
one way to get around

00:13:10.680 --> 00:13:13.872
this would be to assume it
went the average distance

00:13:13.872 --> 00:13:15.830
and the average weight,
and then multiply those

00:13:15.830 --> 00:13:18.410
together, and then multiply
it by the number of shipments.

00:13:18.410 --> 00:13:20.250
It won't be exact,
but it'll be closer,

00:13:20.250 --> 00:13:23.214
because if you just add them
up and then multiply them,

00:13:23.214 --> 00:13:25.130
you're going to be off
by orders of magnitude.

00:13:25.130 --> 00:13:29.810
So in terms of the calculations,
that was just one of the things

00:13:29.810 --> 00:13:33.791
I saw that that is
tricky to look out for.

00:13:33.791 --> 00:13:35.050
The emissions factor.

00:13:35.050 --> 00:13:37.460
So we only gave you
a limited set here.

00:13:37.460 --> 00:13:40.300
But if you go out and look at
the greenhouse gas protocol,

00:13:40.300 --> 00:13:42.740
there will be an emissions
factor for basically every type

00:13:42.740 --> 00:13:43.240
of fuel.

00:13:43.240 --> 00:13:47.070
So you'll have coal, natural
gas, fuel oil, diesel,

00:13:47.070 --> 00:13:49.140
gasoline-- all
different sort of ones.

00:13:49.140 --> 00:13:52.100
So even though we
just basically did

00:13:52.100 --> 00:13:54.730
electricity and
diesel in here, there

00:13:54.730 --> 00:13:56.460
are a whole host
of other factors.

00:13:56.460 --> 00:13:58.970
So if you have a
company that's consuming

00:13:58.970 --> 00:14:02.680
different types of energy,
the same principle applies.

00:14:02.680 --> 00:14:05.990
You know how many cubic feet
of natural gas you consumed,

00:14:05.990 --> 00:14:07.570
and you know its factor.

00:14:07.570 --> 00:14:09.340
For most companies,
you're not going

00:14:09.340 --> 00:14:11.794
to really need much more than
this to do the calculations,

00:14:11.794 --> 00:14:13.460
because most companies
aren't doing much

00:14:13.460 --> 00:14:18.320
other than either burning fuel,
either in furnaces or bunkers

00:14:18.320 --> 00:14:21.500
or in vehicles or
consuming electricity.

00:14:21.500 --> 00:14:23.690
They do make some
specialized calculators

00:14:23.690 --> 00:14:27.030
for different sectors-- cement
manufacturing, certain chemical

00:14:27.030 --> 00:14:28.507
production, paper pulp.

00:14:28.507 --> 00:14:30.090
Things that actually
produce emissions

00:14:30.090 --> 00:14:32.280
through, say, different
chemical processes that are not

00:14:32.280 --> 00:14:33.446
going to be covered by that.

00:14:33.446 --> 00:14:36.670
But for the most part, most
companies and most facilities

00:14:36.670 --> 00:14:38.930
are just going to be able
to be done by these pretty

00:14:38.930 --> 00:14:40.230
simple calculations.

00:14:42.910 --> 00:14:46.220
And just in terms of the actual
underlying mechanics of this.

00:14:46.220 --> 00:14:48.740
So most of the time, when
we're talking about a carbon

00:14:48.740 --> 00:14:51.340
footprint, we're talking about
the six gases that are usually

00:14:51.340 --> 00:14:52.930
known as the Kyoto gases.

00:14:52.930 --> 00:14:55.670
These are the six gases that
were covered under the Kyoto

00:14:55.670 --> 00:14:56.820
Protocol.

00:14:56.820 --> 00:15:00.010
Carbon dioxide, especially
in transportation and fuel

00:15:00.010 --> 00:15:03.410
consumption, is by far
the largest contributor.

00:15:03.410 --> 00:15:05.480
They usually also produce
perhaps a little bit

00:15:05.480 --> 00:15:07.240
of methane, nitrous oxide.

00:15:07.240 --> 00:15:10.610
And other processes might
produce HFCs, PFCs, sulfur

00:15:10.610 --> 00:15:12.770
hexafluoride.

00:15:12.770 --> 00:15:16.060
There are other gases that
contribute to global warming,

00:15:16.060 --> 00:15:17.530
other greenhouse gases.

00:15:17.530 --> 00:15:19.790
But they're not necessarily
covered under Kyoto.

00:15:19.790 --> 00:15:21.930
So this is just something
to look out for,

00:15:21.930 --> 00:15:24.810
especially refrigerants
and some of the others

00:15:24.810 --> 00:15:27.360
that were covered under
the ozone, the Montreal

00:15:27.360 --> 00:15:29.240
Protocol, which covered ozone.

00:15:29.240 --> 00:15:30.917
Since they were already
being regulated,

00:15:30.917 --> 00:15:32.750
they weren't included
in the Kyoto Protocol.

00:15:32.750 --> 00:15:35.160
So a lot of things, especially
like the greenhouse gas

00:15:35.160 --> 00:15:38.590
protocol, don't require
you to measure those.

00:15:38.590 --> 00:15:40.990
But you can measure those
and report them separately,

00:15:40.990 --> 00:15:46.210
because they do contribute to
the overall greenhouse effect.

00:15:46.210 --> 00:15:48.690
Our emissions
factors are usually

00:15:48.690 --> 00:15:52.690
represented in a single unit,
carbon dioxide equivalence.

00:15:52.690 --> 00:15:55.525
Essentially we're trying
to measure different gases,

00:15:55.525 --> 00:15:57.650
contribute to global warming
and different amounts,

00:15:57.650 --> 00:16:01.120
based on how much radiative
forcing they cause.

00:16:01.120 --> 00:16:04.570
So essentially, every
kilogram of methane,

00:16:04.570 --> 00:16:09.170
say, contributes, say, as much
global warming as 34 kilograms

00:16:09.170 --> 00:16:10.392
of carbon dioxide.

00:16:10.392 --> 00:16:11.850
So essentially what
would happen is

00:16:11.850 --> 00:16:14.770
that every kilogram of
methane you would multiply

00:16:14.770 --> 00:16:17.380
by its global warming
potential to determine

00:16:17.380 --> 00:16:20.900
how much carbon dioxide
that would be equivalent to.

00:16:20.900 --> 00:16:23.190
And so all of these
factors that we give

00:16:23.190 --> 00:16:26.290
are in terms of carbon
dioxide equivalence.

00:16:26.290 --> 00:16:29.820
So they're incorporating the
amount of methane and nitrous

00:16:29.820 --> 00:16:32.660
oxide that might be
emitted in there as well.

00:16:32.660 --> 00:16:34.240
Part of this is that
these constantly

00:16:34.240 --> 00:16:36.281
get updated-- or not
constantly, but occasionally

00:16:36.281 --> 00:16:38.320
updated as part of
the IPCC process.

00:16:38.320 --> 00:16:41.830
So they actually just
released in 2013,

00:16:41.830 --> 00:16:43.970
I think, the fifth
version of this.

00:16:43.970 --> 00:16:45.720
And so some of these
factors have changed.

00:16:45.720 --> 00:16:47.095
So that's something
to keep track

00:16:47.095 --> 00:16:50.160
of, especially for a company
that's doing it long term.

00:16:50.160 --> 00:16:51.996
Those factors can
change as you go,

00:16:51.996 --> 00:16:54.370
which sometimes means you need
to go back and recalculate

00:16:54.370 --> 00:16:55.540
and figure it.

00:16:55.540 --> 00:16:58.282
And one thing to be careful
for is that people typically

00:16:58.282 --> 00:16:59.740
refer to things as
carbon footprint

00:16:59.740 --> 00:17:01.370
or the amount of
carbon they're doing.

00:17:01.370 --> 00:17:03.161
Sometimes when they
say that, they actually

00:17:03.161 --> 00:17:05.109
mean just the carbon dioxide.

00:17:05.109 --> 00:17:07.630
Most the time it includes
all of these gases.

00:17:07.630 --> 00:17:10.432
But you should be careful
and look out for that,

00:17:10.432 --> 00:17:12.140
and make sure you're
stating that upfront

00:17:12.140 --> 00:17:13.681
when you're doing
this sort of thing,

00:17:13.681 --> 00:17:17.910
whether you included all of
these or just carbon dioxide.

00:17:17.910 --> 00:17:22.099
The other thing we asked in
here was the emission scopes.

00:17:22.099 --> 00:17:25.869
So this is actually
pretty straightforward.

00:17:25.869 --> 00:17:27.540
Once you think about
what is included

00:17:27.540 --> 00:17:29.750
in your organizational
boundary and whatnot,

00:17:29.750 --> 00:17:32.630
scope one is direct
emissions, right?

00:17:32.630 --> 00:17:35.370
They're direct because
you could put a CO2

00:17:35.370 --> 00:17:36.860
to monitor and
actually monitor it,

00:17:36.860 --> 00:17:38.984
because they're directly
coming from your facility,

00:17:38.984 --> 00:17:41.620
either from your burning
fuels usually or from one

00:17:41.620 --> 00:17:42.850
of those chemical processes.

00:17:42.850 --> 00:17:44.460
So they're the
emissions that are

00:17:44.460 --> 00:17:46.570
coming from the
vehicles you own--

00:17:46.570 --> 00:17:49.020
they're yours-- or
within your facilities,

00:17:49.020 --> 00:17:51.780
directly coming at those
facilities, usually basically

00:17:51.780 --> 00:17:53.700
through fossil fuel combustion.

00:17:53.700 --> 00:17:55.856
Scope two are the
indirect emissions

00:17:55.856 --> 00:17:56.980
that come from electricity.

00:17:56.980 --> 00:18:00.037
So your facility is
consuming electricity.

00:18:00.037 --> 00:18:01.620
Those emissions are
actually occurring

00:18:01.620 --> 00:18:03.703
at the power plant, where
they're burning the coal

00:18:03.703 --> 00:18:05.660
to supply that electricity.

00:18:05.660 --> 00:18:07.900
So we report that
as a separate scope,

00:18:07.900 --> 00:18:10.890
because most companies
and most buildings

00:18:10.890 --> 00:18:13.420
are making use of electricity.

00:18:13.420 --> 00:18:17.430
So usually this falls into sort
of the basic minimum carbon

00:18:17.430 --> 00:18:19.930
footprint that we would consider
for an organization-- scope

00:18:19.930 --> 00:18:21.110
one and scope two.

00:18:21.110 --> 00:18:23.490
Scope three is all the other
indirect emissions, right?

00:18:23.490 --> 00:18:26.490
So one thing to remember is
that all these emissions are

00:18:26.490 --> 00:18:28.080
somebody's direct emissions.

00:18:28.080 --> 00:18:30.220
But they may not
necessarily be what you're

00:18:30.220 --> 00:18:31.790
consider your organization.

00:18:31.790 --> 00:18:34.450
So anything that's not in
your scope one or scope two

00:18:34.450 --> 00:18:37.847
is going to be scope three,
probably because it's

00:18:37.847 --> 00:18:38.930
somebody else's scope one.

00:18:38.930 --> 00:18:40.857
So when you're going
through and thinking

00:18:40.857 --> 00:18:42.940
about what's in your
organizational boundary, what

00:18:42.940 --> 00:18:47.040
you've decided as part of your
carbon footprint-- scope one,

00:18:47.040 --> 00:18:48.800
emissions you're
directly producing;

00:18:48.800 --> 00:18:50.370
scope two, the ones
that are coming

00:18:50.370 --> 00:18:53.100
from electricity
that you consume;

00:18:53.100 --> 00:18:55.046
and basically everything
else is scope three.

00:18:58.170 --> 00:19:00.685
AUDIENCE: For transportation,
if I owned a fleet,

00:19:00.685 --> 00:19:02.070
